cmdc0de 31-Jul-17 03:31 PM
@everyone glad everyone enjoyed the badge. I'm happy to set up a chat on why we made the decisions we did for the badge the last 3 years. specifically around the number of badges, how complex we make them, what challenges go on them, etc. We do a complete review every year before we start the next years. to provide some visibility: the 1000 badges we had this year meant we got a $10K loan and 3 of us funded the remaining ~$20K. So part of the problem of making more badges is the up front cost, so we are looking at other funding methods in the future. Is there interest in having an open discussion on this topic if so I'd be happy to set one up with myself and Krux

defcon25-badge - Badge Related items for defcon 25

so have python installed, satisfy the imports (most likely just openocd for most users), and point the arguments correctly

but that's less fun

er surface mount

wifighost 05-Aug-17 01:10 PM
here is the jist of the origin of this badge project: (edited)
If you haven't read Neal Stephenson's The Diamond Age: or, A Young Lady's Illustrated Primer If you have, there's a sequence around page 300 in which Miranda is first introduced to the possibility of using the drummers to find Nell. In this scene she attends a party in which the revellers wear colorful cloisonné dragonfly pins. As the party progresses they transition from random colorful flickering to some sort of synchrony, and Miranda notices the participants do the same. This is what was built A Sympetrum is a genus of Dragonfly. (edited)

krux 09-Aug-17 06:48 PM
The source is available, as well as a pre-compiled binary on our github page. The capacitive touch is a little finicky. the last three buttons (9, 0 and switch hook) are particularly insensitive, so you have to press them fairly firmly, and make sure that your other hand is touching the USB to ground yourself.
https://github.com/thedarknet/defcon25-badge/tree/master/software
thedarknet/defcon25-badge
defcon25-badge - Badge Related items for defcon 25

Can also buy a segger jlink-edu if you just want it for things like badges and personal stuff. strategicpause 17-Aug-17 10:59 PM
For those who have the st-link cable and want to flash their badge: install st-util, which can be found here: https://github.com/texane/stlink. Once it's installed you can use the command st-flash --format=ihex write firmware.hex to flash your badge. The firmware can be found in the defcon25-badge github project.

BigTaro 02-Oct-17 05:36 PM
Anyone build a badge with a bunch of WS2812B?
krux 03-Oct-17 08:51 AM
I'm not a fan of them.. they are very temperature sensitive, and I don't like the 1wireish protocol it uses
pii100 03-Oct-17 09:22 AM
i want to play with the apa102
BigTaro 03-Oct-17 02:32 PM
@krux Thanks, I was debating between neopixel and dotstar, I guess APA102s are the way to go then
krux 03-Oct-17 06:59 PM
They are also heat sensitive, but they are nicer to control
pii100 03-Oct-17 07:31 PM
I guess that's got to be expected with the size of the package and no thermal pad
krux 04-Oct-17 01:19 PM
the issue is their construction.. the lens and body expand at different rates, and so that can destroy the bond wires.. they also absorb moisture, so if you solder them when "wet" you will get a bubble if steam which flexes the lense and destroys the bond wires. oh, and if you are doing a reflow oven, at temperatures required for ROHS lead free...they can melt. in short, they are neat, but a pain to work with.
pii100 04-Oct-17 07:29 PM
Oh, that kind of temp issues! Explains a lot of the hand soldering on badges
BigTaro 09-Oct-17 06:13 PM
@krux thanks for the pointers

cmdc0de 31-Dec-17 09:49 PM
So spent several days over break laying out a dev board for DC26......
krux 07-Jan-18 10:57 AM
going to rant here for a minute. you know the people who try and sell their darknet badge that they already assembled, for way above what we sold them for, really annoy me. kind of the whole point is that it's a kit, and thus something you have soldered together yourself. If anything it has less value at that point. we also publish the BOM and design files, so you can make a badge yourself. I see eBay listings for a used, often incomplete, badge go for way more than it would cost you do have a single run of a board made, and source the additional parts you need at one off prices. I.e. the most inefficient and least cost effective method to make a badge is still cheaper than what people try to sell them for. I would love to see a group of players get together and have a small run of the boards made. there is a ton you learn from doing such a process, and that's way more in the spirit of why we run this contest.
GuloGuloDesu 07-Jan-18 01:27 PM
Preach on brother Krux!
pharo 08-Jan-18 12:50 PM
Lamers...
Tawnos 09-Jan-18 08:18 AM
@krux It sucks, but what can ya do?
krux 09-Jan-18 11:00 AM
make it well known that spending $200-$360 on a darknet badge, unless you are doing it to raise money for charity, is a rip off. just getting one of the boards made through Macrofab is $89. and you have some other parts you have to source in the $2-5 range each. if you get multiple made the price goes down rather quickly.

schuranator 10-Apr-18 10:07 AM
@krux for people with a non steady hand would you suggest hot air soldering for smd parts or reflow oven?
krux 10-Apr-18 10:12 AM
hot plate is another option. but if you rest your hand on something it'll be a lot steadier. I use a combination of all options, depending on what I'm doing. though mostly hand soldering and hot air rework. paste flux is key for that.
https://smile.amazon.com/gp/aw/d/B00425FUW2/ref=sxts_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1523380340&sr=1&pi=AC_SX236_SY340_FMwebp_QL65
but if you are doing stuff for the badge, really the method I describe in the instructions works best.. you don't want to use an oven or hot plate on it, as it already has parts on it (edited)
schuranator 10-Apr-18 10:20 AM
Ok perfect thank you
Do you have a recommended solder iron hot air setup you use?
krux 11-Apr-18 10:58 AM
I've heard good things about the Quick hot air stations, though I haven't used one. I have an Aoyue 968A+ that I used for awhile and still use for hot air.. I had to repair it when I got it, as it looked like it got dropped in the factory before it was packaged and secured for shipping. so... Kind of lame, but an easy fix of some electrical tape to patch the air system that was cracked. my soldering station is a Metcal, but it's a bit spendy... I'd suggest a Hakko. I've been really impressed with their build quality. once dropped one on a hard floor and there was not even a scratch on it. worked fine. though the UI kind of sucks to adjust the temperature.
schuranator 16-Apr-18 06:22 PM
Thank you @krux I just picked up the Aoyue 968A+ it fit my budget. I'm looking to make my own unofficial badge for personal use and learning. So this will be a big help

Skybye 26-Jul-18 09:18 AM
Ok so I have a semi random question I am listening to Daemon book on audible. I always thought Daemon was pronounced Day-mon but the reader keeps pronouncing it Dee-mon I do not have the book in print form so I am unable to look at how it is spelled in the book in general. My question is have I been wrong in my understanding that the word is pronounced Day-mon or is the reader pronouncing it incorrect or is there a different scenario where we are both correct?
|)3vice 26-Jul-18 09:32 AM
I think it depends on your culture, although this is probably a good place to find out, I would be interested to know what others think too. For me the 'ae' version is pronounced different and has a different meaning from the 'ē' spelling and pronunciation. the a daemon has less to do with good and evil for me, and I pronounce it Day-mon when referring to a running process. There has been a long standing pun in Unix circles that seems to be hinted at in the books. The reader in the audiobook may feel that it adds to the mystery of good or evil intent, as well as divine power by pronouncing it that way. ...At least that is the excuse I make for the mispronunciation IMHO. (edited)
babint 26-Jul-18 09:34 AM

krux 20-Aug-18 12:02 AM
Keep in mind, that those are APA-106 LEDs and there is no code on the badge (unless you write it) to control them. So out of the box they are just blue and bright as hell.
i.e. that's what those LEDs do when they get power. If you solder in the APA-102 SMD leds on the back they will be off unless you write something to drive them.
We wanted to have code to drive them, but ran out of time.

You can also oder the dev boards: https://www.amazon.com/Xiuxin-Development-Dual-Mode-Bluetooth-Antenna/dp/B079PVCF2G/ref=sr_1_1_sspa?ie=UTF8&qid=1534791498&sr=8-1-spons&keywords=esp32&psc=1

r00 24-Aug-18 10:45 PM
After waiting a week for the Adafruit delivery, it turns out that although the badge assembly guide states that you need APA-102s for the back of the badge, you actually need APA-102c. FYI to anyone trying to add LEDs to the backside.
The c's are 5mm while the standard 102s are 2mm and won't work out for you .
You may also be able to substitute APA-102 5050 as well. The APA-102 2020 is far too small to mount.

It’s a sticking point with Burners if someone calls it a festival
It’s a community-based event with communities living by the 10 Principles. (edited)
Most people are Burners year-round, and while there is music, the core of it centers around practicing the principles. That, and Burns are run by community members and boards who do not get paid. And there are no for-profit Burns, and musicians play cuz they want to—they aren’t paid. (edited)

|)3vice 07-Sep-18 09:40 PM
ya, and no clean usually means 'can not clean'. I like 60/40 no-flux and use a flux pen and clean with isopropyl
dont bother with led free (edited)
JoyKil 09-Sep-18 01:07 PM
Link
Tawnos 09-Sep-18 02:05 PM
Eutectic solder (e.g. 63/37) really helps, as does liquid flux/flux pen (even when there's rosin core already). Getting away from conical tips and using chisel tips is also a major help
|)3vice 09-Sep-18 05:15 PM
yup, never underestimate good solder. https://amzn.to/2wYQd3I
I like a chisel tip too, but recently decided I like doing small electronics with a needle tip (C1 has a chisel on the needle tip). will probably go back and forth. (edited)
|)3vice 09-Sep-18 05:25 PM
the other big key to frustration free soldering is a digitally temp controlled soldering iron like the TS100 https://amzn.to/2oUm55V or The Hakko FX-600 https://amzn.to/2NuDgsB
they are both good and portable. The Hakko is better for sustained heat. I also have a Weller WES51 for laying down lots of heat, like soldering on a racing quad PDB.
oh, and the other thing about rosin core is that it smokes really harmful chemicals. I had to stop using it, even with my elaborite fan/filter system because I reacted too it so bad.
regular led solder doesnt hardly smoke at all

Your solder iron tips should be sized to what you are soldering. The tip should be the same size as the pad, as you should be evenly heating the pad and the lead before laying the solder down. (edited)

krux 22-Nov-18 10:07 AM
Nice. One mistake I saw people make when assembling is not pay close enough attention and solder the lipo battery connector on backwards, where it would hang off the edge of the board. So try not to do that one since that lets the smoke out of some of the components.
I always suggest reading through all of the instructions first before starting.

How are you trying to flash the board? Do you have a stlink? The usb is only for power, but that's a mistake a lot of people make.
r00 07-Apr-19 01:25 PM
Not USB @krux St link.

krux 07-Apr-19 01:29 PM
Well too flash the chip all you have to have is power, ground, and the two data lines to the chip. Nothing else matters. Make sure you've also updated the firmware on the stlink itself. I'd also double check your pinout on the programmer, as I have seen different versions that were wired differently.

r00 21-Apr-19 08:49 PM
The 24? That’s the one where the mask can ground out power if you’re not careful right?
krux 21-Apr-19 10:06 PM
That's the one soldering wise yea.
but the big problem is with how I did the keyboard matrix. It also shared pins with the LEDs, and due to size and space there should have been more protection resistors.
